#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:2
msgid "Fish for bash users"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:4
msgid ""
"This is to give you a quick overview if you come from bash (or to a lesser "
"extent other shells like zsh or ksh) and want to know how fish differs. Fish "
"is intentionally not POSIX-compatible and as such some of the things you are "
"used to work differently."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:6
msgid ""
"Many things are similar - they both fundamentally expand commandlines to "
"execute commands, have pipes, redirections, variables, globs, use command "
"output in various ways. This document is there to quickly show you the "
"differences."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:11
msgid "Command substitutions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:13
msgid ""
"Fish spells command substitutions as ``$(command)`` or ``(command)``, but "
"not ```command```."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:15
msgid ""
"In addition, it only splits them on newlines instead of $IFS. If you want to "
"split on something else, use :doc:`string split <cmds/string-split>`, :doc:"
"`string split0 <cmds/string-split>` or :doc:`string collect <cmds/string-"
"collect>`. If those are used as the last command in a command substitution "
"the splits they create are carried over. So::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:17
msgid "for i in (find . -print0 | string split0)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:19
msgid "will correctly handle all possible filenames."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:22
msgid "Variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:24
msgid ""
"Fish sets and erases variables with :doc:`set <cmds/set>` instead of "
"``VAR=VAL`` and a variety of separate builtins like ``declare`` and "
"``unset`` and ``export``. ``set`` takes options to determine the scope and "
"exportedness of a variable::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:26
msgid ""
"# Define $PAGER *g*lobal and e*x*ported,\n"
"# so this is like ``export PAGER=less``\n"
"set -gx PAGER less\n"
"\n"
"# Define $alocalvariable only locally,\n"
"# like ``local alocalvariable=foo``\n"
"set -l alocalvariable foo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:34
msgid "or to erase variables::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:36
msgid "set -e PAGER"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:39
msgid "``VAR=VAL`` statements are available as environment overrides::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:41
msgid "PAGER=cat git log"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:44
msgid ""
"Fish does not perform word splitting. Once a variable has been set to a "
"value, that value stays as it is, so double-quoting variable expansions "
"isn't the necessity it is in bash. [#]_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:46
msgid "For instance, here's bash"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:48
msgid ""
"> foo=\"bar baz\"\n"
"> printf '\"%s\"\\n' $foo\n"
"# will print two lines, because we didn't double-quote\n"
"# this is word splitting\n"
"\"bar\"\n"
"\"baz\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:57
msgid "And here is fish::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:59
msgid ""
"> set foo \"bar baz\"\n"
"> printf '\"%s\"\\n' $foo\n"
"# foo was set as one element,\n"
"# so it will be passed as one element, so this is one line\n"
"\"bar baz\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:65
msgid ""
"All variables are \"arrays\" (we use the term \"lists\"), and expanding a "
"variable expands to all its elements, with each element as its own argument "
"(like bash's ``\"${var[@]}\"``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:67
msgid ""
"> set var \"foo bar\" banana\n"
"> printf %s\\n $var\n"
"foo bar\n"
"banana"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:72
msgid "Specific elements of a list can be selected::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:74
msgid "echo $list[5..7]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:76
msgid ""
"The arguments to ``set`` are ordinary, so you can also set a variable to the "
"output of a command::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:78
msgid ""
"# Set lines to all the lines in file, one element per line\n"
"set lines (cat file)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:81
msgid "or a mixture of literal values and output::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:83
msgid ""
"> set numbers 1 2 3 (seq 5 8) 9\n"
"> printf '%s\\n' $numbers\n"
"1\n"
"2\n"
"3\n"
"5\n"
"6\n"
"7\n"
"8\n"
"9"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:94
msgid ""
"A ``=`` is unnecessary and unhelpful with ``set`` - ``set foo = bar`` will "
"set the variable \"foo\" to two values: \"=\" and \"bar\". ``set foo=bar`` "
"will print an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:96
msgid "See :ref:`Shell variables <variables>` for more."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:98
msgid ""
"zsh also does not perform word splitting by default (the SH_WORD_SPLIT "
"option controls this)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:103
msgid "Wildcards (globs)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:105
msgid ""
"Fish only supports the ``*`` and ``**`` glob (and the deprecated ``?`` glob) "
"as syntax. If a glob doesn't match it fails the command (like with bash's "
"``failglob``) unless the command is ``for``, ``set`` or ``count`` or the "
"glob is used with an environment override (``VAR=* command``), in which case "
"it expands to nothing (like with bash's ``nullglob`` option)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:107
msgid "Globbing doesn't happen on expanded variables, so::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:109
msgid ""
"set foo \"*\"\n"
"echo $foo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:112
msgid "will not match any files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:114
msgid ""
"There are no options to control globbing so it always behaves like that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:116
msgid ""
"The ``**`` glob will match in subdirectories as well. In other shells this "
"often needs to be turned on with an option, like ``setopt globstar`` in bash."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:118
msgid ""
"Unlike bash, fish will also follow symlinks, and will sort the results in a "
"natural sort, with included numbers compared as numbers. That means it will "
"sort e.g. music tracks correctly even if they have numbers like ``1`` "
"instead of ``01``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:120
msgid "See :ref:`Wildcards <expand-wildcard>` for more."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:123
msgid "Quoting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:125
msgid ""
"Fish has two quoting styles: ``\"\"`` and ``''``. Variables are expanded in "
"double-quotes, nothing is expanded in single-quotes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:127
msgid ""
"There is no ``$''``, instead the sequences that would transform are "
"transformed *when unquoted*::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:129
msgid ""
"> echo a\\nb\n"
"a\n"
"b"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:133
msgid "See :ref:`Quotes <quotes>` for more."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:136
msgid "String manipulation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:138
msgid ""
"Fish does not have ``${foo%bar}``, ``${foo#bar}`` and ``${foo/bar/baz}``. "
"Instead string manipulation is done by the :doc:`string <cmds/string>` "
"builtin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:140
msgid "For example, to replace \"bar\" with \"baz\"::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:142
msgid ""
"> string replace bar baz \"bar luhrmann\"\n"
"baz luhrmann"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:145
msgid "It can also split strings::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:147
msgid ""
"> string split \",\" \"foo,bar\"\n"
"foo\n"
"bar"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:151
msgid "Match regular expressions as a replacement for ``grep``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:153
msgid ""
"> echo bababa | string match -r 'aba$'\n"
"aba"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:156
msgid "Pad strings to a given width, with arbitrary characters::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:158
msgid ""
"> string pad -c x -w 20 \"foo\"\n"
"xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxfoo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:161
msgid "Make strings lower/uppercase::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:163
msgid ""
"> string lower Foo\n"
"foo\n"
"\n"
"> string upper Foo\n"
"FOO"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:169
msgid ""
"repeat strings, trim strings, escape strings or print a string's length or "
"width (in terminal cells)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:172
msgid "Special variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:174
msgid "Some bash variables and their closest fish equivalent:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:176
msgid "``$*``, ``$@``, ``$1`` and so on: ``$argv``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:177
msgid "``$?``: ``$status``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:178
msgid "``$$``: ``$fish_pid``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:179
msgid "``$#``: No variable, instead use ``count $argv``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:180
msgid "``$!``: ``$last_pid``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:181
msgid "``$0``: ``status filename``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:182
msgid "``$-``: Mostly ``status is-interactive`` and ``status is-login``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:185
msgid "Process substitution"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:187
msgid ""
"Instead of ``<(command)`` fish uses ``(command | psub)``. There is no "
"equivalent to ``>(command)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:189
msgid ""
"Note that both of these are bashisms, and most things can easily be "
"expressed without. E.g. instead of::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:191
msgid "source (command | psub)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:193
msgid "Use::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:195
msgid "command | source"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:197
msgid "as fish's :doc:`source <cmds/source>` can read from stdin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:200
msgid "Heredocs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:202
msgid "Fish does not have ``<<EOF`` \"heredocs\". Instead of"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:204
msgid ""
"cat <<EOF\n"
"some string\n"
"some more string\n"
"EOF"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:211
msgid "use::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:213
msgid "printf %s\\n \"some string\" \"some more string\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:215
msgid "or::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:217
msgid ""
"echo \"some string\n"
"some more string\"\n"
"\n"
"# or if you want the quotes on separate lines:\n"
"\n"
"echo \"\\\n"
"some string\n"
"some more string\\\n"
"\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:227
msgid "Quotes are followed across newlines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:229
msgid "What \"heredocs\" do is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:231
msgid ""
"Read/interpret the string, with special rules, up to the terminator. [#]_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:232
msgid "Write the resulting string to a temporary file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:233
msgid "Start the command the heredoc is attached to with that file as stdin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:235
msgid "This means it is essentially the same as just reading from a pipe, so::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:237
msgid "echo \"foo\" | cat"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:239
msgid "is mostly the same as"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:241
msgid ""
"cat <<EOF\n"
"foo\n"
"EOF"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:247
msgid ""
"Like with heredocs, the command has to be prepared to read from stdin. "
"Sometimes this requires special options to be used, often giving a filename "
"of ``-`` turns it on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:249
msgid "For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:251
msgid ""
"echo \"xterm\n"
"rxvt-unicode\" | pacman --remove -\n"
"\n"
"# is the same as (the `-` makes pacman read arguments from stdin)\n"
"pacman --remove xterm rxvt-unicode"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:257
msgid "and could be written in other shells as"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:259
msgid ""
"# This \"-\" is still necessary - the heredoc is *also* passed over stdin!\n"
"pacman --remove - << EOF\n"
"xterm\n"
"rxvt-unicode\n"
"EOF"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:267
msgid ""
"So heredocs really are minor syntactical sugar that introduces a lot of "
"special rules, which is why fish doesn't have them. Pipes are a core "
"concept, and are simpler and compose nicer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:269
msgid ""
"For example, the \"EOF\" is just a convention, the terminator can be an "
"arbitrary string, something like \"THISISTHEEND\" also works. And using ``<<-"
"`` trims leading *tab* characters (but not other whitespace), so you can "
"indent the lines, but only with tabs. Substitutions (variables, commands) "
"are done on the heredoc by default, but not if the terminator is quoted: "
"``cat << \"EOF\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:272
msgid "Test (``test``, ``[``, ``[[``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:274
msgid ""
"Fish has a POSIX-compatible ``test`` or ``[`` builtin. There is no ``[[`` "
"and ``test`` does not accept ``==`` as a synonym for ``=``. It can compare "
"floating point numbers, however."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:276
msgid ""
"``set -q`` can be used to determine if a variable exists or has a certain "
"number of elements (``set -q foo[2]``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:279
msgid "Arithmetic Expansion"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:281
msgid ""
"Fish does not have ``$((i+1))`` arithmetic expansion, computation is handled "
"by :doc:`math <cmds/math>`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:283
msgid "math $i + 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:285
msgid "Unlike bash's arithmetic, it can handle floating point numbers::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:287
msgid ""
"> math 5 / 2\n"
"2.5"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:290
msgid "And also has some functions, like for trigonometry::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:292
msgid ""
"> math cos 2 x pi\n"
"1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:295
msgid ""
"You can pass arguments to ``math`` separately like above or in quotes. "
"Because fish uses ``()`` parentheses for :ref:`command substitutions <bash-"
"command-substitutions>`, quoting is needed if you want to use them in your "
"expression::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:297
msgid "> math '(5 + 2) * 4'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:299
msgid ""
"Both ``*`` and ``x`` are valid ways to spell multiplication, but ``*`` needs "
"to be quoted because it looks like a :ref:`glob <bash-globs>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:302
msgid "Prompts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:304
msgid ""
"Fish does not use the ``$PS1``, ``$PS2`` and so on variables. Instead the "
"prompt is the output of the :doc:`fish_prompt <cmds/fish_prompt>` function, "
"plus the :doc:`fish_mode_prompt <cmds/fish_mode_prompt>` function if :ref:"
"`vi mode <vi-mode>` is enabled. The output of the :doc:`fish_right_prompt "
"<cmds/fish_right_prompt>` function is used for the right-sided prompt."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:306
msgid "As an example, here's a relatively simple bash prompt:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:308
msgid ""
"# <$HOSTNAME> <$PWD in blue> <Prompt Sign in Yellow> <Rest in default light "
"white>\n"
"PS1='\\h\\[\\e[1;34m\\]\\w\\[\\e[m\\] \\[\\e[1;32m\\]\\$\\[\\e[m\\] '"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:313
msgid "and a rough fish equivalent::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:315
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    set -l prompt_symbol '$'\n"
"    fish_is_root_user; and set prompt_symbol '#'\n"
"\n"
"    echo -s (prompt_hostname) \\\n"
"    (set_color blue) (prompt_pwd) \\\n"
"    (set_color yellow) $prompt_symbol (set_color normal)\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:324
msgid "This shows a few differences:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:326
msgid ""
"Fish provides :doc:`set_color <cmds/set_color>` to color text. It can use "
"the 16 named colors and also RGB sequences (so you could also use "
"``set_color 5555FF``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:327
msgid ""
"Instead of introducing specific escapes like ``\\h`` for the hostname, the "
"prompt is a function. To achieve the effect of ``\\h``, fish provides helper "
"functions like :doc:`prompt_hostname <cmds/prompt_hostname>`, which prints a "
"shortened version of the hostname."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:328
msgid ""
"Fish offers other helper functions for adding things to the prompt, like :"
"doc:`fish_vcs_prompt <cmds/fish_vcs_prompt>` for adding a display for common "
"version control systems (git, mercurial, svn), and :doc:`prompt_pwd <cmds/"
"prompt_pwd>` for showing a shortened ``$PWD`` (the user's home directory "
"becomes ``~`` and any path component is shortened)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:330
msgid ""
"The default prompt is reasonably full-featured and its code can be read via "
"``type fish_prompt``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:332
msgid ""
"Fish does not have ``$PS2`` for continuation lines, instead it leaves the "
"lines indented to show that the commandline isn't complete yet."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:335
msgid "Blocks and loops"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:337
msgid ""
"Fish's blocking constructs look a little different. They all start with a "
"word, end in ``end`` and don't have a second starting word::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:339
msgid ""
"for i in 1 2 3; do\n"
"   echo $i\n"
"done\n"
"\n"
"# becomes\n"
"\n"
"for i in 1 2 3\n"
"   echo $i\n"
"end\n"
"\n"
"while true; do\n"
"   echo Weeee\n"
"done\n"
"\n"
"# becomes\n"
"\n"
"while true\n"
"   echo Weeeeeee\n"
"end\n"
"\n"
"{\n"
"   echo Hello\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"# becomes\n"
"\n"
"begin\n"
"   echo Hello\n"
"end\n"
"\n"
"if true; then\n"
"   echo Yes I am true\n"
"else\n"
"   echo \"How is true not true?\"\n"
"fi\n"
"\n"
"# becomes\n"
"\n"
"if true\n"
"   echo Yes I am true\n"
"else\n"
"   echo \"How is true not true?\"\n"
"end\n"
"\n"
"foo() {\n"
"   echo foo\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"# becomes\n"
"\n"
"function foo\n"
"    echo foo\n"
"end\n"
"\n"
"# (bash allows the word \"function\",\n"
"#  but this is an extension)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:396
msgid "Fish does not have an ``until``. Use ``while not`` or ``while !``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:399
msgid "Subshells"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:401
msgid ""
"Bash has a feature called \"subshells\", where it will start another shell "
"process for certain things. That shell will then be independent and e.g. any "
"changes it makes to variables won't be visible in the main shell."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:403
msgid "This includes things like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:405
msgid ""
"# A list of commands in `()` parentheses\n"
"(foo; bar) | baz\n"
"\n"
"# Both sides of a pipe\n"
"foo | while read -r bar; do\n"
"    # This will not be visible outside of the loop.\n"
"    VAR=VAL\n"
"    # This background process will not be, either\n"
"    baz &\n"
"done"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:418
msgid ""
"Fish does not currently have subshells. You will have to find a different "
"solution. The isolation can usually be achieved by scoping variables (with "
"``set -l``), but if you really do need to run your code in a new shell "
"environment you can use ``fish -c 'your code here'`` to do so explicitly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:420
msgid ""
"``()`` subshells are often confused with ``{}`` grouping, which does *not* "
"use a subshell. When you just need to group, you can use ``begin; end`` in "
"fish::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:422
msgid ""
"(foo; bar) | baz\n"
"# when it should really have been:\n"
"{ foo; bar; } | baz\n"
"# becomes\n"
"begin; foo; bar; end | baz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:428
msgid ""
"The pipe will be run in the same process, so ``while read`` loops can set "
"variables outside::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:430
msgid ""
"foo | while read bar\n"
"    set -g VAR VAL\n"
"    baz &\n"
"end\n"
"\n"
"echo $VAR # will print VAL\n"
"jobs # will show \"baz\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:438
msgid ""
"Subshells are also frequently confused with :ref:`command substitutions "
"<bash-command-substitutions>`, which bash writes as ```command``` or "
"``$(command)`` and fish writes as ``$(command)`` or ``(command)``. Bash also "
"*uses* subshells to implement them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:441
msgid "Builtins and other commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:443
msgid ""
"By now it has become apparent that fish puts much more of a focus on its "
"builtins and external commands rather than its syntax. So here are some "
"helpful builtins and their rough equivalent in bash:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:445
msgid ""
":doc:`string <cmds/string>` - this replaces most of the string "
"transformation (``${i%foo}`` et al) and can also be used instead of ``grep`` "
"and ``sed`` and such."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:446
msgid ""
":doc:`math <cmds/math>` - this replaces ``$((i + 1))`` arithmetic and can "
"also do floats and some simple functions (sine and friends)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:447
msgid ""
":doc:`argparse <cmds/argparse>` - this can handle a script's option parsing, "
"for which bash would probably use ``getopt`` (zsh provides ``zparseopts``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:448
msgid ""
":doc:`count <cmds/count>` can be used to count things and therefore replaces "
"``$#`` and can be used instead of ``wc``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:449
msgid ""
":doc:`status <cmds/status>` provides information about the shell status, e."
"g. if it's interactive or what the current linenumber is. This replaces ``$-"
"`` and ``$BASH_LINENO`` and other variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:451
msgid ""
"``seq(1)`` can be used as a replacement for ``{1..10}`` range expansion. If "
"your OS doesn't ship a ``seq`` fish includes a replacement function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:454
msgid "Other facilities"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:456
msgid ""
"Bash has ``set -x`` or ``set -o xtrace`` to print all commands that are "
"being executed. In fish, this would be enabled by setting :envvar:"
"`fish_trace`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../fish_for_bash_users.rst:458
msgid ""
"Or, if your intention is to *profile* how long each line of a script takes, "
"you can use ``fish --profile`` - see the :doc:`page for the fish command "
"<cmds/fish>`."
msgstr ""
